title: For Sale:  Glock 9mm extended magazine NY Safe Act compliant for Glock 17 19 26
postcontent:
The following is a unique Glock 9mm magazine. It is a KCI brand Glock 9mm extended magazine originally intended to hold 33 rounds. However, it has been modified to only accommodate eight rounds. This has been achieved using a magazine block that has been permanently welded to the follower and the magazine spring (see picture). As well, the +2 round extended base plate has been replaced with a flat base plate. If you wanted the maximum 10 rounds currently allowed by the NY Safe ACT you could simply replace the base plate.

Why would I do this to such a magazine? Personally, at one time I was interested in the aesthetic of the ridiculous protruding magazine to have my Glock 17 fit the profile of a G18 seen in certain movies and video games. However, I only use standard 10 round magazines now, and am doing some spring cleaning and looking to sell the magazine.

$20 for the magazine, either FTF or shipping is additional.

NY SAFE ACT compliance source: Since 1994, magazines sold in New York could contain up to 10 rounds. This continues to be true today. You may buy, sell, and possess any magazine that can hold up to 10 rounds, regardless of when it was manufactured. If you have a magazine that can contain more than 10 rounds, you have until January 15, 2014 to permanently modify the magazine so that it holds no more than ten rounds, responsibly discard it, transfer it to a law enforcement agency or officer, or sell it to a dealer or an out of state purchaser.

Call or text 3 one 5 2 5 six 3 six seven 4. No emails please.

title: For Sale:  Winchester Model 70 30-06 pre 1964
postcontent:
This gun belonged to my grandfather. It was passed down to relatives after his death in 1986, and I wound up with it a few years ago. It had been stored in a case for decades, and probably had not been fired since the late 1960s. I cleaned it up and test-fired it. I shot a 2” group at 100 yards the first time out… but your mileage may vary!

Here is what I know about the gun’s condition:

- It shoots well

- There was some missing finish (lacquer or shellac) on the stock near the butt end. I lightly buffed this area with a fine scotchbrite pad to remove the loose flakes, and applied a light coat of linseed oil followed by carnauba wax. There are some color variations remaining, but the wood is in good condition and I think that a full refinish would put things right.

- There are some light rub marks in a couple of areas. See photos. I think this is from the sling buckles rubbing during storage and making slight impressions in the wood. The finish is intact in these areas. These can likely be sanded smooth during a refinish.

- It has a Weaver K4 60-B scope. There is a scuff on the top and a small dent on the underside as shown in the photos.

- There is no rear sight. The sight was likely removed and the filler block installed when the scope was added.

- There was some rust on the butt plate. I applied rust remover, followed by a cold bluing treatment. It looks OK now, but a professional restoration would make it like new.

- In general, the bluing is in good condition. The exception is several areas on the top right of the barrel. There is some light pitting which is shown in the pictures.

- The serial number is from 1949 per Winchester. The underside of the barrel is stamped “1906 49.” The bolt carries the full serial number, which matches the receiver number.

- The sling is included, but it’s rough. There is a missing rivet at one end, and the leather is very dry and stiff.

Armslist limits me to 5 photos; I have uploaded many more to my website:

http://www.geagan.com/p227145187

I will also email these photos upon request.

Sorry, no trades.

I am also selling:

Steyr M9-A1 9mm
